      "title": "See also"
    },
    {
      "blocks": [
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "The Hanning window is defined as"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "formulas": [
            "w(n) = 0.5 - 0.5\\cos\\left(\\frac{2\\pi{n}}{M-1}\\right) \\qquad 0 \\leq n \\leq M-1"
          ],
          "type": "math_block"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "The Hanning was named for Julius von Hann, an Austrian meteorologist.\nIt is also known as the Cosine Bell. Some authors prefer that it be\ncalled a Hann window, to help avoid confusion with the very similar\nHamming window."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "Most references to the Hanning window come from the signal processing\nliterature, where it is used as one of many windowing functions for\nsmoothing values.  It is also known as an apodization (which means\n\"removing the foot\", i.e. smoothing discontinuities at the beginning\nand end of the sampled signal) or tapering function."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        }
      ],
      "title": "Notes"
    },
    {
      "blocks": [
        {
          "raw_kind": "footnote",
          "raw_text": "1\n\nBlackman, R.B. and Tukey, J.W., (1958) The measurement of power\nspectra, Dover Publications, New York.",
          "type": "raw_block"
        },
        {
          "raw_kind": "footnote",
          "raw_text": "2\n\nE.R. Kanasewich, \"Time Sequence Analysis in Geophysics\",\nThe University of Alberta Press, 1975, pp. 106-108.",
          "type": "raw_block"
        },
        {
          "raw_kind": "footnote",
          "raw_text": "3\n\nWikipedia, \"Window function\",\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Window_function",
          "type": "raw_block"
        },
        {
          "raw_kind": "footnote",
          "raw_text": "4\n\nW.H. Press,  B.P. Flannery, S.A. Teukolsky, and W.T. Vetterling,\n\"Numerical Recipes\", Cambridge University Press, 1986, page 425.",
          "type": "raw_block"
        }
      ],
      "title": "References"
    },
    {
      "blocks": [
        {
          "lines": [
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "import flopscope as fnp"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "fnp.hanning(12)"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "array([0.        , 0.07937323, 0.29229249, 0.57115742, 0.82743037,"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "       0.97974649, 0.97974649, 0.82743037, 0.57115742, 0.29229249,"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "       0.07937323, 0.        ])"
            }
          ],
          "type": "doctest_block"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "Plot the window and its frequency response."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "argument_inline": [],
          "content_blocks": [
            {
              "language": "python",
              "text": "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\nfrom fnp.fft import fft, fftshift\nwindow = fnp.hanning(51)\nplt.plot(window)\nplt.title(\"Hann window\")\nplt.ylabel(\"Amplitude\")\nplt.xlabel(\"Sample\")\nplt.show()\n\nplt.figure()\nA = fft(window, 2048) / 25.5\nmag = fnp.abs(fftshift(A))\nfreq = fnp.linspace(-0.5, 0.5, len(A))\nwith fnp.errstate(divide='ignore', invalid='ignore'):\n    response = 20 * fnp.log10(mag)\nresponse = fnp.clip(response, -100, 100)\nplt.plot(freq, response)\nplt.title(\"Frequency response of the Hann window\")\nplt.ylabel(\"Magnitude [dB]\")\nplt.xlabel(\"Normalized frequency [cycles per sample]\")\nplt.axis('tight')\nplt.show()",
              "type": "literal_block"
            }
          ],
          "directive": "plot",
          "options": [
            {
              "name": "include-source",
              "value": ""
            }
          ],
          "raw_source": ".. plot::\n    :include-source:\n\n    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n    from numpy.fft import fft, fftshift\n    window = np.hanning(51)\n    plt.plot(window)\n    plt.title(\"Hann window\")\n    plt.ylabel(\"Amplitude\")\n    plt.xlabel(\"Sample\")\n    plt.show()\n\n    plt.figure()\n    A = fft(window, 2048) / 25.5\n    mag = np.abs(fftshift(A))\n    freq = np.linspace(-0.5, 0.5, len(A))\n    with np.errstate(divide='ignore', invalid='ignore'):\n        response = 20 * np.log10(mag)\n    response = np.clip(response, -100, 100)\n    plt.plot(freq, response)\n    plt.title(\"Frequency response of the Hann window\")\n    plt.ylabel(\"Magnitude [dB]\")\n    plt.xlabel(\"Normalized frequency [cycles per sample]\")\n    plt.axis('tight')\n    plt.show()",
          "supported": true,
          "type": "directive_block"
        }
      ],
      "title": "Examples"
    }
